150–1216","1140–1216":"1140–1216","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1170–1244":"1170–1244","1120–1153":"1120–1153","1119–Female":"1119–Afdød","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","4 December 1214":"4. december 1214","1244":"1244","1144":"1144","between 1140 and 1150":"fra 1140 til 1150","1143":"1143","1153":"1153","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1119":"1119","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Skotland","Scotland":"Skotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, East Lothian, Skotland, United Kingdom","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"between 1140 and 1150–1216":"van 1140 to 1150–1216","1140–1216":"1140–1216","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1170–1244":"1170–1244","1120–1153":"1120–1153","1119–Female":"1119–Overleden","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","4 December 1214":"4 december 1214","1244":"1244","1144":"1144","between 1140 and 1150":"van 1140 to 1150","1143":"1143","1153":"1153","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1119":"1119","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, East Lothian, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Schotland"},"en":{"between 1140 and 1150–1216":"from 1140 to 1150–1216","1140–1216":"1140–1216","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1170–1244":"1170–1244","1120–1153":"1120–1153","1119–Female":"1119–Deceased","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","4 December 1214":"4 December 1214","1244":"1244","1144":"1144","between 1140 and 1150":"from 1140 to 1150","1143":"1143","1153":"1153","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1119":"1119","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Hythus was born from 1140 to 1150, in Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland, her father, Adam de Hythus, was 31 and her mother, Hythus, was 32. She had at least 1 daughter with William 'The Lion' King of Scotland. She died in 1216, in Scotland, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"between 1140 and 1150–1216":"1140 kuni 1150–1216","1140–1216":"1140–1216","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1170–1244":"1170–1244","1120–1153":"1120–1153","1119–Female":"1119–Surnud","1216":"1216","1214":"1214","4 December 1214":"4. detsember 1214","1244":"1244","1144":"1144","between 1140 and 1150":"1140 kuni 1150","1143":"1143","1153":"1153","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1119":"1119","Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland":"Dunfermline, Fife, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Haddington, East Lothian, Scotland":"Haddington, East Lothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Stirling, Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"between 1140 and 1150–1216":"vuodesta 1140 vuoteen 1150–1216","1140–1216":"1140–1216","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1170–12